<br>
you are a idiot ;-)<br>
<br>
if it wasn't for democracy, you wouldn't be able to post that dumb ass post ya did.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, you are entirely wrong. Democracy has zero to do with my right to free speach - that right is guaranteed in the Constitution. The anonymity of the internet has nothing to do with it either. Anyone with any gumption could get my full name, street address and who knows what else. Not to mention the fact that I am quite open about the fact that i am opposed to the idea of democracy in real life.<br>
<br>
So why exactly am I an idiot? Because i don't agree with YOU on what good government is? Because I don't believe that a government that rules on behalf of 50% +1 of it's people rahter than all of them is good government? (Hell it doesn't even have to be a majority, it could be a plurality). Because I don't blindly accept that democratic government = good government the way society raises us to do, and the way you did?<br>
<br>
And yes, it is true that the U.S is not a pure democracy in that we do not all vote on every policy that is put in place. However, a Republic is a form of democracy, as it is founded upon the idea of giving the power to the people, whether it be by directly instituting policy by majority vote (like propositions) or through popular elections to determine which officials will make the decisions about American policy.<br>
<br>
Have you ever actually thought about what democracy implies? The pury theory of it is faulty for the reason i mentioned above (it does not rule on behalf of all of it's people). If I am of a minority opinion, then I am ruled by policies put in place and enforced on me by other people solely because they outnumber me and those that think the way i do. There's another word for that besides democracy - it's called oppression.<br>
<br>
This of course says nothing about the temporal problems of our government. That is, ideas of what's good and bad policy change with each generation, yet it is much more difficult to take something back than it is to implement it in the first place. For example, what if even 100% of the people today wanted to abolish the income tax (a tax originally unconstitutional, yet amended into the constitution because of the majority opinion at the time of the great depression)? Despite even the fact that there are enough people to overcome the safeguards designed to prevent an amendment from being removed, do you think it would happen now that the U.S government relies on it so heavily?<br>
<br>
As for the asanine, sarcastic post about theocracy, you are engaging in a logical fallacy known as a false dillema. That is, you present an alternative as if it is the only one so that any rational human being would obviously believe the alternative that you provide (in this case democracy, which was already provided). Nice try, twit. If you do actually believe that a Theocracy is the best form of government, more power to you and sorry for calling you a twit.<br>
<br>
Now, real life presents far more problems than theory would lead on. Ideally, everyone in a democracy would be fully informed of all issues and canditates. Unfortunately, the people of which this is true are in a small minority. The rest (the majority) are uninformed dickheads. Their &quot;information&quot; comes from bias campaign adds full of misinformation and flat out LIES. Votes are won not by objective information given to the people, but by the person who gets the most publicity and whoever does the best job of getting people to believe their bullshit. Campaigns are more about proving the oponent wrong than whether or not the initial person/policy is actually RIGHT. Example you ask? Sure thing: here in Arizona there were three gambling propositions on the Nov. 5th ballot. Props 200 201 and 202. All three were designed at least in part to expand gaming on Indian reservations. All 3 increase the number of slot machine allowed in casinos as well as allowing tribes to share machines. All three also allowed for a certain number of house banked table games (blackjack, poker, and in the case of 200 craps and baccarat). 201 would also allow racetracks to have a certain number of slot machines (significantly less than any of the reservation casinos) but would not get the benefit of house banked tables. Now nevermind the fact that all of these are propositions designed to affect the monopolistic/oligopolistic strength of the casinos (something that Americans hate if an entrepenuer achieves, yet are all for it if the government creats one, like the post office, indian gamind etc...). Prop 200 had the least exposure and not surprisingly lost by something like an 80% 20% vote. Prop 201 and 202 had teh most TV exposure, and both adds amounted to bullshittting about the other proposition. 202 was an especially good source of crap. The 201 adds stated that 202 closes books completely to the public about how much the casino makes. The 202 adds stated that it grants full disclosure. Well which is it? At least one of them is full of it. The truth is that they BOTH were. 202 would grant partial disclosure of some funds (although I forget the specifics). Yay for misrepresentation, and in the end the truth was NEVER given in any of the adds. Then there were the 202 adds that try to play on people sympathy, and teh name The 17 Tribe Innitiative like that makes in any less of a piece of shit. But wait there's more! In one 202 add that aired near election time, some Indian get on camera and states (this is word-for-word) &quot;A yes vote on proposition 202 is needed to continue Indian Gaming.&quot; This is a FLAT OUT FUCKING LIE. If none of the three passed, not a god damn thing would have changed in terms of indian gaming. 202 just benefits the tribes that support it most, and all any of them do is EXPAND the gaming that is already in place. In case you're wondering, no, I'm not finished with this particular campaign. The final example of the retarded practice of &quot;informing&quot; voters is that all of the indian casinos in the Phoenix area (you know, where 90% of the state's gamblers go?) were in support of Prop. 202. So the people that these 3 propositions most affect go in to gamble and are bombarded with &quot;Vote yes on 202&quot; rhetoric crap with no counter to that. Nevermind the fact that the information they get is totally biased and in many cases untrue, but the 202 thupers get a huge advantage that neither of the other 2 recieved. So their target audience comes into their casino and hears shit like &quot;We need a yes vote to continue gaming.&quot; Well, guess which proposition passed, and which 2 failed miserably?<br>
<br>
Seriously, if we are going to practice flawed government, can we at least do it the proper fucking way?<br>
<br>
You called me an idiot, care to back it up? Or, unlike me, do you have no reason for believing what you do except that you are raised and you believe the crap you hear on TV that we are doing the world a favor by spreading democratic government etc. etc. You think you have power? Bullshit, your right to vote doesn't give you dick. Your right to vote gives power to the person who does the best job of convincing you to believe something, or to the party to which you blindly follow if that's your thing. The only true political power that people have in the U.S. is granted to them in the constitution, and it ain't democracy--it's the right to keep and bear arms such that if the government ever becomes oppressive we as a people have a way to stop it.<br>
<br>
Look, i don't give a flying fuck if you support democracy or not, but you better believe i am going to be pissed when a bunch of dicks who know nothing about what they are voting for save what the people who want what they vote for to pass tell them pass policies and elect officials that affect me and dictate how I must live my life because the majority said so (and as we all know, the majority MUST be right). For fuck's sake though, have legitimate reasons for believing what you do and don't accept it until you recognize the good, bad, and alternatives in an objective way (i.e. not in the way that you get from tv school newspapers etc). And if you are going to call me an idiot because I have legitament reasons for being an opponent of democracy, you damn well better have some good reasons to back it up instead of weak fallacious crap like &quot;if it wasn't for democracy, you wouldn't be able to post that dumb ass post ya did.&quot;<br>
<br>
Well I know i am forgetting stuff, but I will recall if and when this flame progresses.<br>
<br>
-Saddil <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/bdrinal28133.showUserPublicProfile?gid=saddil242>Saddil242</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><font color=#33cc33>Drinalite</font></span><br>  Posts: 102<br> <font color=#FF0000>(11/6/02 10:12:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1612.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: /flame Democracy</span><hr size=1> Ok it's a few mins later and i remembered some shit. First of all, Cuthulus, I do agree entirely with you that The U.S. is the greatest country on earth, or I wouldn't be living here. There are quit a few countries that i would love to live in as well (England, Germany and Switzerland all come to mind) but bottom line is I prefer America to them. However, why is it that so many people accept the idea of relative good as being absolute good? Is shitty government good just because it's better than the rest of the world's shitty government? And I also agree with you in that I am happy for the Republican party. I don't have any real affiliation but in the clusterfuck that is the two party system I'd rather Republicans tell me what to do than Democrats, at least in most cases.<br>
